A table of contents (TOC) can be automatically generated in a LaTeX document using the `\tableofcontents` (TOC) command, combined with sectioning commands like `\section`, `\subsection`, and others. Here's an example demonstrating how to create a TOC in a LATEX document:

**Document Template (my_document.tex):**

```latex
\documentclass{report}
\usepackage{tocloft}

\begin{document}

\tableofcontents

\section{Introduction}
\subsection{Background and Motivation}
\subsection{Objectives}
\section{Methods}
\subsection{Data Collection}
\subsection{Data Analysis}
\section{Results}
\subsection{Quantitative Findings}
\subsection{Qualitative Insights}
\section{Discussion}
\subsection{Interpretation of Results}
\subsection{Limitations and Future Work}

\end{document}
```

**Command to Generate Table of Contents:**

Add the following line to your preamble after loading the necessary packages (if not done already):

```latex
\tableofcontents
```

**Result:**

When you compile your LaTeX document with this template and the TOC command, it will generate an automatically-updated table of contents in the generated PDF file. The TOC will include section and subsection headings with their respective page numbers, making it easy for readers to navigate your document.

Note: To customize the appearance and layout of the table of contents, you can modify the TOC-related settings via `tocloft` package commands, such as `\renewcommand{\cfttoctitlefont}{\hfill\bfseries}` (for bold title) or `\renewcommand{\cftsecnumwidth}{2.5em}` (to increase section number width).

To draw a FEN (Forsyth–Edwards Notation) chessboard state in LaTeX, you'll need the `tikz` package along with other necessary packages for board setup and piece placement. Here's a LATEX code template to help you get started:

**Required Packages and Commands:**

```latex
\usepackage{tikz}
\usetikzlibrary{positioning}
\usepackage{chessboard} % For chessboard pattern and pieces
```

**LATEX Code:**

```latex
