\usepackage{tikz}
\usetikzlibrary{positioning}
\usepackage{chessboard}

\begin{document}

\begin{tcbsetbox}[x=0.8\textwidth,y=1.5cm,font=small,center]{}% Set TCB area for chessboard
\chessboardset{board}{
  \setchessboard{
    position={
      e2q b3q k7r n5q b6r q1kbnr ppppppppppppppppppp
      PpPpPpPpPppPpPpPpPpPpPpPpPpR
     ..................
     ...................
     .... P.............
     ..................
     ..................
     ...... R...........
     ..................
      qB............. P
     .................
     ................ R
      pPpPpPpPpPpPpPpPpPpPpPpPpPp
    }
  }
}
\end{tcbsetbox}

\begin{center}
  \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
    \chessboardboard{
      \chessboard{board}
    }
  \end{tikzpicture}
\end{center}

\end{document}
```

**Explanation:**

1. `tcbsetbox` and `chessboardset` environments are used for setting up the TCB area and drawing the chessboard using the `chessboard` package.
2. The `position` option within `setchessboard` sets the board's initial position.
3. `scale=0.8` adjusts the size of the chessboard to fit the specified width.
4. `PpPpPpPpPpPpPpPpPpPpR` represents a standard FEN starting position for the white pieces.
5. Compile the LaTeX document to generate the desired chessboard image.

Feel free to modify the code as per your needs and preferences, such as changing colors, piece placements, or adding annotations.

