Here's a Java solution using logarithms to solve the problem without loops or recursion:

```java
public class PowerOfThree {
    public static boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        if (n == 0) return n == 1; // Base cases: 0 and 1 are powers of three

        if (n < 0) return false; // Negative numbers can't be powers of three

        int power = (int) Math.log(n) / Math.log(3);
        return (power - Math.floor(power)) == 0; // Check if the result is an integer (i.e., a perfect power)
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(27));   // true
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(0));    // true
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(-1));  // false
    }
}
```

This solution works by checking if the given number `n` is equal to 1 (base case) or negative (which cannot be a power of three). Then, it calculates the power to which 3 must be raised to obtain `n` using logarithms. If the resulting power (after rounding down to the nearest integer) matches the original power, then it's a perfect power of three.

The time complexity of this solution is O(1), making it efficient even for large inputs.

